Seattle Police Use of Force Analysis¶

Problem¶

The Black Lives Matter movement has highlighted the disporoportionate use of force by police officers on the Black community. Public data from the Seattle Police Department (SPD) was used to explore the policing of communities of color.

Conclusions¶

  • Black residents are more likely to be involved in SPD use of force incidents
    • Looking at the number of use of force incidents by race, there are an abnormally high number of incidents involving Black civilians.
    • Incidents also seem high for American Indian, Alaska Native, Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander populations, but due to low population numbers this is less definitive.
    • White civilians were involved in slightly fewer UoF incidents than expected.
    • Perhaps surprisingly, Hispanic, Latinx and Asian civilians had the fewest incidents recorded.
    • Over 18% of incidents had no race reported for the civilian, which could greatly impact this analyis.

  • Certain officers are much more likely to use force
    • Most officers have very few use of force incidents reported (blue density in the left bottom corner).
    • The officers with many use of force incidents and those that have a higher ratio of serious incidents to less serious ones (above the trendline) seem to be disproportionately involved in Officer Involved Shootings (red X).
    • This data does not tell us about officers that never generate UoF incidents, how long officers are on the force, how many arrests officers make without generating use of force reports, or if the officers involved in more use of force incidents have roles -- like being part of the SWAT team -- that would explain their high levels of forceful interactions.

  • Some precints seem better at de-escalation
    • Looking at precinct level trends, the Southwest Precinct stands out for having low levels of use of force incidents, incidents per officer, officer involved shootings, and low ratio of more serious use of force to less serious perhaps suggesting a culture of de-escalation.

  • Use of force incidents tend to happen in areas with elevated crime rates
    • There is a very strong spatial correlation between rates of interpersonal crimes and "crimes against society" and use of force incidents.
    • The correlation with property crime is very weak, perhaps because fewer arrests are made in these types of crimes, or when the arrest is made it happens away from the neighborhood of the property crime.
    • Data on actual arrest and ticketing locations was not available, and would help clarify if use of force is applied evenly as a percentage of police encounters in each neighborhood.

  • Use of force incidents track the overall crime rate over time
    • Reporting on use of force began under a consent decree with the Department of Justice in 2014. Incidents of UoF trended down until the beginning of 2017, rose through 2017 and 2018, then fell dramatically in the beginning of 2019, staying low since.
    • The timing of these changes may be related to federal enforcement of the consent decree, but this also generally tracks the overall crime rate for the city, so may just reflect the number of police-civilian arrests and interractions.
    • Because force reports are filed by the police themselves, poor reporting and better policing would have identical impacts on the data.

#accumulator df
census_tract_demo = pd.DataFrame()

# just get King county demographics
fips = ['53033']

for fip in fips:
    county_tract = censusdata.download('acs5', 2018, censusdata.censusgeo([('state', fip[:2]), ('county', fip[2:]), ('tract', '*')]),
                                    ['B01002_001E', 'B19013_001E', 'B01001_001E', 'B01001_003E', 'B01001_004E', 'B01001_005E', 
                                     'B01001_006E', 'B01001_007E', 'B01001_008E', 'B01001_009E', 'B01001_010E', 'B01001_020E', 
                                     'B01001_021E', 'B01001_022E', 'B01001_023E', 'B01001_024E', 'B01001_025E', 'B01001_027E', 
                                     'B01001_028E', 'B01001_029E', 'B01001_030E', 'B01001_031E', 'B01001_032E', 'B01001_033E', 
                                     'B01001_034E', 'B01001_044E', 'B01001_045E', 'B01001_046E', 'B01001_047E', 'B01001_048E', 
                                     'B01001_049E', 'C17002_001E', 'C17002_002E', 'C17002_003E', 'C17002_004E', 'C17002_005E',
                                     'B03002_001E', 'B03002_003E', 'B03002_004E', 'B03002_005E', 'B03002_006E', 'B03002_007E', 
                                     'B03002_012E', 'B07013_001E', 'B07013_002E',
                                    ])
    county_tract = county_tract.reset_index()
    county_tract = county_tract.rename(columns=decoder)

    # loop through tracts to create aggregate statistics
    iter_ = county_tract.copy()
    for row in iter_.itertuples():
        # get geocode for merging with map
        geocode = fip + str(row.index)[-6:]
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'geocode'] = geocode
        
        # get income level information
        try:
            low_income_pct = (row.income_to_poverty_lt_point_5 + \
                         row.income_to_poverty_point_5_to_1 + \
                         row.income_to_poverty_1_to_1_point_24 + \
                         row.income_to_poverty_1_point_24_to_1_point_49) / \
                         row.income_to_poverty_total_count
        except:
            low_income_pct = np.nan
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'low_income_pct'] = low_income_pct
        
        # get racial composition of area
        try: 
            pct_white = row.count_white / row.count_all_races
            pct_black = row.count_black / row.count_all_races
            pct_latinx = row.count_latinx / row.count_all_races
            pct_ai_na = row.count_ai_na / row.count_all_races
            pct_asian = row.count_asian / row.count_all_races
            pct_hawaiian_pi = row.count_hawaiian_pi / row.count_all_races
        except:
            pct_white, pct_black, pct_latinx, pct_ai_na, pct_asian = np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, np.nan
        
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pct_white'] = pct_white
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pct_black'] = pct_black
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pct_latinx'] = pct_latinx
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pct_ai_na'] = pct_ai_na
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pct_asian'] = pct_asian
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pct_hawaiian_pi'] = pct_hawaiian_pi
        
        # get home ownership
        try:
            pct_homeowner = row.owner_occupied_residence / row.all_residence
        except:
            pct_homeowner = np.nan
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pct_homeowner'] = pct_homeowner

        # get age breakdown
        try:
            pct_child = (row.male_under_5 + row.male_5_9 + row.male_10_14 + row.male_15_17 \
                        + row.female_under_5 + row.female_5_9 + row.female_10_14 \
                        + row.female_15_17) / row.total_age
            pct_uni = (row.male_18_19 + row.male_20 + row.male_21 + row.male_22_24 \
                      + row.female_18_19 + row.female_20 + row.female_21 \
                      + row.female_22_24) / row.total_age
            pct_senior = (row.male_65_66 + row.male_67_69 + row.male_70_74 + row.male_75_79 \
                         + row.male_80_84 + row.male_85_over + row.female_65_66 + row.female_67_69 \
                         + row.female_70_74 + row.female_75_79 + row.female_80_84 \
                         + row.female_85_over) / row.total_age
        except:
            pct_child, pct_uni, pct_senior = np.nan, np.nan, np.nan
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pct_child'] = pct_child
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pct_uni'] = pct_uni
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pct_senior'] = pct_senior

        # estimate size of census tract population
        county_tract.loc[row.Index, 'pop_estimate'] = max([row.all_residence, row.count_all_races, \
                                    row.income_to_poverty_total_count, row.total_age])
    
    # keep aggregates stats
    keep_cols = ['geocode', 'pop_estimate', 'median_age', 'pct_child', 'pct_uni', 'pct_senior', 
                 'median_household_income', 'low_income_pct', 'pct_homeowner', 'pct_white', 
                 'pct_black', 'pct_latinx', 'pct_asian', 'pct_ai_na', 'pct_hawaiian_pi', 
                 'count_white', 'count_black', 'count_latinx', 'count_ai_na', 'count_asian',
                 'count_hawaiian_pi']

    # append aggregate data to accumulator
    census_tract_demo = pd.concat([census_tract_demo, county_tract[keep_cols]], axis = 0)

    
# name the columns for the accumulator dataframe
census_tract_demo.columns = keep_cols

# Use one hot encoding to get counts of incident types by officer
incidents = pd.get_dummies(spd_uof['Incident_Type'])
incidents = incidents.rename(columns={'Level 1 - Use of Force' : 'UoF_1'})
incidents.loc[:, 'UoF_2_and_3'] = incidents.sum(axis=1) - incidents.UoF_1
incidents
incidents_by_officer = pd.concat([spd_uof, incidents], axis=1)

# custom function to assign officers to precints based on where the majority
# of their incidents take place. Eliminates irregular values in the date like
# 'X' and if precints are tied makes the choice by random to avoid systemic bias
valid = ['West', 'North', 'East', 'South', 'Southwest']
def rand_valid(x):
    # options are modal values
    options = [y for y in pd.Series.mode(x) if y in valid]
    
    # if no valid precints, return NaN
    if len(options) == 0:
        return np.nan
    
    # if single valid mode, return that precinct
    elif len(options) == 1:
        return options[0]
    
    # if choice of two or more valid modal precincts, choose at random
    else:
        return choice(options)

# for each officer, count incidents of varying degrees of seriousness
force_incidents = incidents_by_officer.groupby(['Officer_ID']).agg(
    UoF_1 = ('UoF_1', 'sum'),
    UoF_2_and_3 = ('UoF_2_and_3', 'sum'),
    UoF_OIS = ('Level 3 - OIS', 'sum'),
    UoF_total = ('Incident_Type', 'count'),
    Precinct = ('Precinct', rand_valid),
)
plt.figure(figsize=(16,6));
sns.distplot(force_incidents['UoF_total'], kde=False);
plt.title('Distribution of officers generating use of force incidents',
          fontdict = {'fontsize' : 14});

How have Use of Force Incidents trended over time?¶

In [20]:
# choosing period of March 2015 through Feb 2020, five years with consistent police boundaries
# and avoid COVID, BLM protests and incidents not yet being logged in the system
# because using a rolling average, going to a rolling average number of days before the time period

# How many days of smoothing to use, how far apart should peak labels be 
SMOOTH = 56
SEPARATE = 56

# set start date and end date of the plot
roll_start = date(2015, 3, 1)
end = date(2020, 2, 28)

# grab days from before the start for the rolling average
delta = timedelta(days=SMOOTH-1)
start = roll_start - delta

# add a column for just the date of the use of force incident,
# aggregate by date over by range
spd_uof.loc[:,'date'] = spd_uof['Occured_date_time'].dt.date
incidents_by_day = spd_uof.loc[(spd_uof['date'] >= start)
                               & (spd_uof['date'] <= end)].groupby(
                                    spd_uof['date'], as_index= False).agg(
    dates = ('date', 'first'),
    uof_incidents = ('Subject_ID', 'nunique'),
)

# add a column for just the date of the crime,
# aggregate by date over by range and ignore property crimes
seattle_crime.loc[:,'date'] = seattle_crime['Offense Start DateTime'].dt.date
crimes_by_day = seattle_crime.loc[(seattle_crime['date'] >= start)
                                  & (seattle_crime['date'] <= end)
                                  & (seattle_crime['Crime Against Category'].isin(['SOCIETY', 'PERSON']))].groupby(
                                    seattle_crime['date'], as_index= False).agg(
    dates = ('date', 'first'),
    crimes = ('Offense ID', 'count'),
)

crime_uof_by_day = crimes_by_day.merge(incidents_by_day,
                                       on = 'dates',
                                       how = 'left').fillna(0).set_index('dates')

In [21]:
# take a SMOOTH day rolling average to smooth the data. SMOOTH should be a multiple of 7 
# to negate any day of the week effects, smooth out spordic events
# to look at monthly/seasonal effects
crime_uof_by_day.loc[:, 'uof_rolling'] = crime_uof_by_day['uof_incidents'].rolling(SMOOTH).mean()
crime_uof_by_day.loc[:, 'crime_rolling'] = crime_uof_by_day['crimes'].rolling(SMOOTH).mean()

# pull the date back into a column, dropna, and add a column for easy to read date format
crime_uof_by_day = crime_uof_by_day.dropna().reset_index()
crime_uof_by_day.loc[:, 'date_str'] = crime_uof_by_day['dates'].apply(lambda x: pd.Timestamp(x).strftime('%b %d'))

# I wanted to label the five highest peaks and lowest troughs in the data
NUM_LABELS = 10

# find dates when the data goes from increasing to decreasing
data = crime_uof_by_day['uof_rolling'].values
doublediff = np.diff(np.sign(np.diff(data)))
peak_locations = np.where(doublediff == -2)[0] + 1

# find dates when the data goes from decreasing to increasing
doublediff2 = np.diff(np.sign(np.diff(-1*data)))
trough_locations = np.where(doublediff2 == -2)[0] + 1

# for each peak location, annotate with the full date, peak height, and date string
peak_heights = []
for peak in peak_locations:
    date_str = str(crime_uof_by_day.loc[peak, 'date_str'])
    incidents = crime_uof_by_day.loc[peak, 'uof_rolling']
    date_ = crime_uof_by_day.loc[peak, 'dates']
    peak_heights.append([date_, incidents, date_str])

# for each trough location, annotate with the full date, peak height, and date string
trough_heights = []
for trough in trough_locations:
    date_str = str(crime_uof_by_day.loc[trough, 'date_str'])
    incidents = crime_uof_by_day.loc[trough, 'uof_rolling']
    date_ = crime_uof_by_day.loc[trough, 'dates']
    trough_heights.append([date_, incidents, date_str])
In [23]:
# sort the peaks in descending order, troughs in ascending order
peak_heights = sorted(peak_heights, key=lambda x: x[1])[::-1]
trough_heights = sorted(trough_heights, key=lambda x: x[1])

# I also wanted unique peaks, so I wanted to block out three days 
# on either side of each peak to show unique peaks in the data
blocked_dates = []
unique_peaks = []
date_range = timedelta(days=SEPARATE)
delta = timedelta(days=1)

for peak in peak_heights:
    date_ =  peak[0]
    if date_ in blocked_dates:
        continue
    unique_peaks.append(peak)
    start = date_ - date_range
    end = date_ + date_range
    while start <= end:
        blocked_dates.append(start)
        start += delta

# Repeat the same process for troughs
blocked_dates = []
unique_troughs = []

for trough in trough_heights:
    date_ =  trough[0]
    if date_ in blocked_dates:
        continue
    unique_troughs.append(trough)
    start = date_ - date_range
    end = date_ + date_range
    while start <= end:
        blocked_dates.append(start)
        start += delta
    
# turn the peaks into a dataframe for plotting
unique_peaks_df = pd.DataFrame(unique_peaks[:NUM_LABELS])
unique_peaks_df.columns = ['DateFormat', 'Avg_Daily_Incidents', 'Date_Str']

# turn the troughs into a dataframe for plotting
unique_troughs_df = pd.DataFrame(unique_troughs[:NUM_LABELS])
unique_troughs_df.columns = ['DateFormat', 'Avg_Daily_Incidents', 'Date_Str']

Milestone 2: Generate and evaluate a working model (linear, or time series)¶

In [25]:
# helper functions

# plot ACF and PACF from Seth
def plot_acf_pacf(x, lags = 40):
    x = x[x.notna()] # remove NAs
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (15, 5))
    fig = splt.plot_acf(x, lags = lags, ax = axes[0])
    fig = splt.plot_pacf(x, lags = lags, ax = axes[1]);
    return None

# plot time series and residuals from Seth
def plot_ts_resid(x):
    x = x[x.notna()] # remove NAs
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (15, 5))
    fig = sns.lineplot(x.index, x, ax = axes[0])
    fig = sns.distplot(x, ax = axes[1]);
    return None

# Dicky-Fuller test from Seth
# tests null hypothesis that time series is non-stationary
def DF_Test(ts):
    ts = ts[ts.notna()]
    stationary = adfuller(ts)
    print('D-F statistic = ' + str(stationary[0]))
    print('p-value = ' + str(stationary[1]))
    print('number of lags used = ' + str(stationary[2]))
    print('Critical value at 5% confidence = ' + str(stationary[4]['5%']))
    print('Critical value at 10% confidence = ' + str(stationary[4]['10%']))
    return None

# STL decomposion from Seth
def decomp_ts(ts, period, model = 'additive'):
    res = sts.seasonal_decompose(ts, model = model, period = period)
    return(pd.DataFrame({'ts': ts, 'trend': res.trend, 'seasonal': res.seasonal, 'resid': res.resid}, 
                        index = ts.index))

Time Series Model Evaluation¶

  • The 56 day rolling average for use of force incidents by Seattle police officers appears to behave like a random walk, with a strong partial correlation with the prior day and erratic, perhaps spurious partial correlations with prior days
  • STL decomposition was attempted at periods of 366 (yearly), 57 (the moving average window) and 2 (the previos day). All three resulted in residuals closer to white noise than the original data, with the 2 day period having the most significant effect.
  • An auto-ARIMA technique was employed to confirm that differencing alone provided the best transformation of the time series to stationary data. Indeed, an ARIMA(0,1,0)(0,0,0) model was the best fit for the data.
  • Unfortunately, all these models indicate that if there are any seasonal trends to the use of force by SPD, they are dwarfed by randomness, making the model practically useless for forecasting future trends
